Oh how I missed you, Ming's Cafe. I used to come here almost every Saturday morning with my family before dropping off my kids to New York Chinese School. We enjoy their breakfast options with a mix of traditional Chinese and western food. Since my kids have graduated I don't get to visit as much. Glad they've reopen after Covid lockdown and are doing their best to adopt safety measures to continue to provide good affordable food to the community again. I highly recommend that you support this small business.

Good simple Cantonese style quick meal. I ordered a few items, my go to are congee, curry fishballs and rice noodles. Their fried turnips are flavorful. I am not expecting 5 star meals here. The price is affordable, it is clean and made fresh to order. The service is efficient and friendly. A local grease spoon joint; old New York. I like the modern HK style eateries too but we have to keep local places like this going as they too contribute to what makes NYC cuisine great. There is a little outdoor seating area set up, you place your order and take a seat. Cash only I think...Next door is a busy coffee bar if you need caffeine...this corner is quite lively.

I can't believe I'm giving this rating to a place where I couldn't finish the food, but the curry udon noodles with tripe were everything I expected from Hong Kong food. Not being able to stomach the food was on me, not the restaurant. I want to come back again and again to experience foods I couldn't possibly experience otherwise. Even the tripe - something I have never been able to eat elsewhere - was good enough I almost finished my plate. Try everything. I'll be back, happily.

Prices seem to go up every year. Used to be $4 something or $5 for a meal, just 4 or 5 years ago.  Too much corn-starch or potato-starch in the sauces, typical toisan-style. I came in because the reviews were great and the price was right. I had no idea what to order so I perused the Google review photos and pointed one out, a beef and noodle dish, to the helpful gentleman behind the counter... He said it was one of their more popular dishes and it truly was delicious. I had it with scallion pancakes with sauce on the side, equally comforting on a cold night. It was A LOT of food and I am a big guy so you will definitely get your $'s worth here.  Service was great too they assumed I was taking to-go and when they learned I was staying offered to transfer my food to a nice dish. Definitelye will be back.

Ming’s cafe has to be the best American/Asian breakfast spot in lower Manhattan and Chinatown. Whether you want a basic omelette or even to try out a small dim sum appetizer or even late lunch, they are the most economical and best in service!! It’s around the corner from the East Broadway (F Train station). They have pictures to show you their selections and Ming is fast and accurate with our orders every time. It is in a casual eat and run or takeout setting but oh so delicious every time!!! Thanks Ming for a delicious set breakfast that my family  loves! They are open early and have ready made menu items like noodles and congee for you to pickup when pressed for time.

The lone survivng business on this once neglected piece of real estate on the corner of Canal and Essex Street. There is a reason for their continue success: traditional home cooked affordable inexpensive tasty food.  Everyone in the community eats here: NYPD, hipsters, seniors, teenagers, children, singles, couples, families, Asians, Latinos, Europeans, Democrats, Republicans, etc.  It is common to see customers come into Ming's and order a $6 meal then go next door and order a $4 coffee or fill up at Ming's before going around the corner to meet their date for an intimate vegan Mexican dinner.  This corner of the LES where so much of NYC converges has changed so much in the past five years...thankfully Ming's has not. A true reflection of a Chinatown long ago.

I ordered a stir fried udon dish and it was really good. Their portion was very generous and I really enjoyed my meal. Service was quick and everyone was really friendly and the prices are very reasonable. Their menu had a lot of options, so I will definitely be back to explore some more. They also have bubble tea and other beverages to select from, but I would definitely recommend the food.

For a wide selection of food on their menu, Ming’s Caffe can satisfy those who are craving some Asian food. My usual from this place would be their boneless chicken-chop over spaghetti. I can never stop eating it since it’s so good. For fewer than seven bucks, you can get yourself a fulfilling meal since they give a lot. You can dine in or take out, but I always prefer to take out since they have very few tables, but dining in would be good too! People here are extremely nice, because they always make their customers feel satisfied with what they ordered, and you can always find yourself welcome to this place. You can watch your food cooked right before your eyes, since the kitchen is right behind the casher, or if you like, you can sit and watch some TV to catch up with some Asian news. Ming’s Caffe also has a breakfast or brunch selection; so if you need food for brunch, just drop by over here since everything on the menu looks good and is affordable.
